. Covering areas such as informal negotiation, text and context, strategy, working with British and American Governments, and offering perceptions of other players involved in the dialogue and negotiations that led to the Good Friday Agreement of 1998 and the power-sharing arrangements that followed, this dramatic account will become a major source for academics and interested readers alike for years to come. Volume one deals with the Irish Government and Sunningdale (1973) and the Anglo-Irish Agreement (1985) and Volume two on the Good Friday Agreement (1998) and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aPolitical Studies 2020. 4aSecurity, Conflict & Peace 2020. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Peace.2bisacsh  aConflict.  aGood Friday Agreement.  aGovernment.  aIrish.  aNegotiation.  aNorthern Ireland.  aPeace Process.  aRepublicans.  aTalks.  aUnionists.1 aSpencer, Graham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614252840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526142528423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526142528/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles